      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hate-Crime Law Cited in Synagogue Attack</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Mazin Assi and Mohammed Alfaqih, two young men accused of vandalizing synagogue in Bronx, are indicted for hate crimes and will be first suspects prosecuted under state's new hate-crime law (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Two young men accused of vandalizing a synagogue in the Bronx were indicted yesterday for hate crimes and will be the first suspects prosecuted under the state's new hate-crime law, the authorities said.</p>
        <p>Mazin Assi, 21, and Mohammed Alfaqih, 18, both of Yonkers, were indicted on hate-crime charges of attempted arson and criminal mischief, Michelle Medley, a spokeswoman for the Bronx district attorney, told The Associated Press.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Two young men accused of vandalizing a synagogue in the Bronx were indicted yesterday for hate crimes and will be the first suspects prosecuted under the state's new hate-crime law, the authorities said.</p>
        <p>Mazin Assi, 21, and Mohammed Alfaqih, 18, both of Yonkers, were indicted on hate-crime charges of attempted arson and criminal mischief, Michelle Medley, a spokeswoman for the Bronx district attorney, told The Associated Press.</p>
        <p>On Oct. 8, prosecutors have said, the two suspects and a 15-year-old boy threw a bottle of vodka at the front door of Conservative Synagogue Adath Israel of Riverdale, on West 250th Street. The juvenile faces charges in family court.</p>
        <p>Under the new hate-crime law, attempted arson carries a maximum sentence of 15 years, more than double the normal maximum.</p>
      </block>
